Take each `Target` in sample python code within the `ELEMENTS` dict and regenerate each `Target` in it's own `CopierDefinition` with the same bucket, source values. Do not change anything that is not expected, just split it into multiple CopierDefinition only.

Use the current name with a index e.g `ust_cms_files_{index}` where `{index}` gets replaced with the index number.

Generate them all in the same Dictionary and use a new name with the index added to the current key. Example:

```python
{
"ust_cms_files_0": CopierDefinition(
       bucket=bucket.SOURCE_BUCKET,
       source="USTHEALTHPROOF/usthealthproof/production/to_clover/cms/",
       targets=[
           Target(
               pattern=r"^F.+\.MONMEMD\.D2",
               destination="milliman/production/from_clover/",
           ),
       ].
 ),
 "ust_cms_files_1": CopierDefinition(
        bucket=bucket.SOURCE_BUCKET,
        source="USTHEALTHPROOF/usthealthproof/production/to_clover/cms/",
        targets=[
            Target(
                 pattern=r"^F.+\.MONMEMD\.D2",
                 destination="care-evolution/production/from_clover/MMRD/",
            ),
        ].
  ),   
}
```

Its ok to combine `Target` in  `CopierDefinition.targets` list if you see that they are dropping files in the same `Target.destination` or their `Target.pattern` is the same.
